  • id: This is only the identifier, so it is not needed for the models.
  • Gender: This should be a categorical variable.
  • Age: This is a numerical data.
  • Driving license: This is a categorical variable and shows if the customer has driving license or not. 1 - has driving license, 0 - does not have driving license
  • License type: This is a categorical variable showing the license type.
  • Region code: This is a categorical variable showing the region code of the customer.
  • Previously insured: This shows if the customer had previously insurance or not, so it is a categorical variable.
  • Vehicle age: This is a categorical variable showing the age of the vehicle, for example 1-2 Year or < 1 Year.
  • Vehicle Damage: This is a categorical variable, if it is 1 then it indicates that the customer got his or her vehicle damaged previously.
  • Annual premium: This is a numerical variable and shows the amount that should be payed yearly.
  • Policy sales channel: This is a categorical variable showing the channel, like over mail or phone for example with codes.
  • Seniority: This shows the number of days the customer has been associated with the company, it is numerical.
  • Target: This is a categorical variable showing if the customer is interested(1) or not(0).

After checking the data types, based on the description the proper types should be set.If it is a categorical variable then factor should be set.

training_data$id <- NULL
factor_variables <- c("Gender","Driving_License","Licence_Type","Region_Code", "Previously_Insured", "Vehicle_Age","Vehicle_Damage","Target","Policy_Sales_Channel")
training_data[factor_variables] <- lapply(training_data[factor_variables], as.factor)

There are 5091 missing values in case of the licence type. There are more kinds of methods for imputing the missing values, however it can introduce biases, so we decided to delete them, since a lot of data will still remain.

training_data <- na.omit(training_data)
training_data$Policy_Sales_Channel <- NULL
training_data$Driving_License <- NULL
  1. Modeling:

For this kind of task, it is a little bit important to use models that are transparent and interpretable. In the context of insurance sales through call centers, understanding which customers are likely to be interested in an offer is crucial.However it is not like deciding about loans as a bank, it is less important here to know all the details, since it is an internal project only, and otherwise someone decides about the order for example or anything else, so why not decide more accurate using models?

We choose the following 3 models (2 is fully interpretable) to test:

  • decision tree
  • logistic regression
  • random forest
  1. Train-Test split with stratified split method: 80% - 20%

Optimal model training

dt_optimal <- rpart(Target ~ ., 
                  data = train_split, method = "class", control = rpart.control(cp = 6.075826e-04),parms = list(split = "information"))
rpart.plot(dt_optimal)

Checking the performance of the optimal model on testing data:

library(caret)

evaluate_model <- function(true_labels, predicted_labels) {
  cm <- confusionMatrix(predicted_labels, true_labels, positive = "1")
  print(cm)
}

predictions <- predict(dt_optimal, newdata = test_split, type = "class")
evaluate_model(test_split$Target, predictions)

coefs <- summary(logistic_backward)$coefficients
coefs_df <- data.frame(Variable = rownames(coefs),
                       Estimate = coefs[, "Estimate"],
                       p_value = coefs[, "Pr(>|z|)"])
coefs_df <- coefs_df[coefs_df$Variable != "(Intercept)", ]
coefs_df$OddsRatio <- exp(coefs_df$Estimate)
coefs_df$Significance <- coefs_df$p_value < 0.05

library(ggplot2)

  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Logistic Regression: Odds Ratios",
